article.headline: Penn scores 26 points on 11-for-13 shooting for USC
article.linkText: Despite fatigue, No. 22 South Carolina still able to win big
article.story:
COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- South Carolina coach Susan Walvius was at
a loss to explain her team's 30 turnovers and 21-point victory.

	   The Gamecocks (No. 22 ESPN/USA Today; No. 23 Associated Press) overcame sloppy play with crisp shooting to
beat Georgia Southern 75-54 Tuesday night.

	   ''I'm just going to write this one off to fatigue,'' said
Walvius, whose team was playing for the first time since winning
two games last weekend at the Paradise Jam tournament in the U.S.
Virgin Islands. ''How we won by 21, I have no idea.''

	   Jocelyn Penn scored 26 points on 11-for-13 shooting and had 11
rebounds as South Carolina (5-0) closed out the victory with a 20-5
run.

	   The Gamecocks shot 31-for-55 (56.4 percent) from the field,
while the Eagles (3-2) shot 23-for-73 (31.5 percent).

	   ''We got the looks we wanted, but we just couldn't find anybody
to put the ball in the hole,'' Georgia Southern coach Rusty Cram
said.

	   The Gamecocks also grabbed 32 offensive boards to Georgia
Southern's 16.

	   Kelly Morrone had 17 points, and Petra Ujhelyi added 13 points
and 12 rebounds for South Carolina.

	   Mimi Lindsey led Georgia Southern with 14 points and seven
rebounds, while Shawnica Hill added 12 points and six boards, and
Tiffany Lanier registered 10 of the Eagles' 19 steals.

	   South Carolina led by 10 at halftime and extended its advantage
to 51-38 with 16 minutes left.

	   But the Gamecocks turned the ball over nine times in the next
eight minutes, and Georgia Southern closed to 53-49 on a jumper
by Adrienne Early with 11:26 left.

	   But the Eagles missed 13 of their next 15 shots and turned the
ball over seven times during South Carolina's 18-5 run.

	   ''Like the mark of a great team, South Carolina found a way to
do what they had to do,'' Cram said.

	   The run took some time to develop. A layup by South Carolina's
Vania Redd made it 55-49. The teams then combined to miss their
next eight shots and commit six turnovers before Penn's layup gave
the Gamecocks an eight-point lead with eight minutes left.

	   Walvius and her players stayed in the locker room for more than
15 minutes after the game, dissecting what the coach called the
Gamecocks' worst game in two years.

	   ''We want to be the best team in the country, but we didn't play
like that tonight,'' Walvius said. ''We looked like we were still
in the Virgin Islands.''

	   Penn agree.

	   ''We knew the game was ugly,'' she said.

	   Twelve of Morrone's points came in the first half, and she hit
three of her five 3-pointers in the run at the end of the first
half.

	   As Georgia Southern guarded Penn, who is averaging 27 points,
Morrone was open.

	   Cram tried to prevent Penn from dominating outside and Ujhelyi
from controlling the inside. So, he gambled and left Morrone open,
hoping the streaky shooter, who was averaging just three points,
would have an off night.

	   But the gamble failed. ''If she's hot, she can shoot with the
best of them,'' Cram said.

	   The Gamecocks take on Wofford on Wednesday night after a
scheduling conflict at the Carolina Center forced the team to play
on consecutive nights.

	   Georgia Southern, which has beaten South Carolina just once in
17 tries, has lost 33 consecutive games to ranked opponents.
